Before deploying a data practice, product teams in
major companies often need to consult internal
privacy experts, either residing in dedicated
stand-alone teams (e.g., a privacy council) or
groups within the product
team~\cite{ThePriva36:online}. These privacy experts
are often a mix of experts from different relevant
areas, such as lawyers, UX researchers, privacy
engineers, software engineers, and product
designers~\cite{cranor2013privacy}. The main goal
for the privacy review is to make sure that the data
practice is legal and involves acceptable risk for
the company’s business~\cite{nistir8062}.
Most existing privacy review frameworks are derived
from Information Security Research, such as
PRAM~\cite{nistir8062draft} and Privacy Impact
Assessment (PIA)~\cite{wright2011privacy}, which
treat privacy in a manner similar to security. For
example, PRAM first asks experts to map data
processing pipeline within the target system, and
catalogs contextual factors, and data
actions\footnote{Data actions are information system
operations that process personal
information~\cite{nistir8062draft}.}.
Experts then enumerate all potential problems
associated with each data action and then assign
scores to the likelihood and severity of each
problem. In this way, builders can quantify and
prioritize privacy risks for the organization (e.g.,
revenue loss from customer abandonment), and
determine appropriate resource allocations to
address the risks. The quality of such a privacy
review is dependent on the experts’ expertise level.
However, these experts are scarce and expensive in
the industry. Indeed, it often takes years for
software engineers to develop skills as a privacy
expert and to gain an appreciation for the interplay
between technical, business, human, and legal
issues~\cite{cranor2013privacy}.
% Most existing privacy review frameworks are
derived from Information Security Research, such as
PRAM~\cite{nistir8062draft} and Privacy Impact
Assessment (PIA)~\cite{wright2011privacy}, which
treat privacy in a manner similar to security. For
example, PRAM first asks experts to map data
processing pipeline within the target system, and
catalogs contextual factors, and data
actions\footnote{Data actions are information system
operations that process personal
information~\cite{nistir8062draft}.}.
% Experts then enumerate all potential problems
associated with each data action and then assign
scores to the likelihood and severity of each
problem. Each likelihood score is multiplied by its
associated severity score to yield a risk metric per
potential problem. The estimated risk per data
action would be the sum of the risks for each
problem associated with the data action. In this
way, builders can quantify and prioritize privacy
risks for the organization (e.g., revenue loss from
customer abandonment), and determine appropriate
resource allocations to address the risks.

AgilePrivacy: Preempting Data Use Backlash using the Crowd1:5•We intro 12 evaluate AgilePrivacy using 12 different data practices with 240 crowd users and24 experts.2 RELATED WORKAgilePrivacy builds on ideas from three different areas: 1) privacy review by experts, 2)understanding users’ privacy needs and 3) privacy surveys.2.1 Privacy Review by ExpertsModern privacy regulations (e.g., Ann Cavoukian [14]) argues that organizations should thinkabout privacy in a proactive manner (i.e., Privacy by Design) rather than a reactive one (traditionalprivacy regulations). Before deploying a data practice, product teams in major companies oftenneed to consult internal privacy experts, either residing in dedicated stand-alone teams (e.g., aprivacy council) or groups within the product team [67]. These privacy experts are often a mix ofexperts from different relevant areas, such as lawyers, UX researchers, privacy engineers, softwareengineers, and product designers [22]. The main goal for the privacy review is to make sure thatthe data practice is legal and involves acceptable risk for the company’s business [73].Most existing privacy review frameworks are derived from Information Security Research, suchas PRAM [72] and Privacy Impact Assessment (PIA) [105], which treat privacy in a manner similarto security. For example, PRAM first asks experts to map data processing pipeline within the targetsystem, and catalogs contextual factors, and data actions5. Experts then enumerate all potentialproblems associated with each data action and then assign scores to the likelihood and severity ofeach problem. In this way, builders can quantify and prioritize privacy risks for the organization(e.g., revenue loss from customer abandonment), and determine appropriate resource allocationsto address the risks. The quality of such a privacy review is dependent on the experts’ expertiselevel. However, these experts are scarce and expensive in the industry, since it often take yearsfor software engineers to develop skills as a privacy expert and to gain an appreciation for theinterplay between technical, business, human, and legal issues [22].Another major approach is guidelines-based, where privacy experts use a set of guidelines todesign and analyze a specific data practice [47]. For example, Fair Information Practice Principles(FIPPS) enumerates a set of guidelines — such as Transparency, Purpose Specification, DataMinimization — that an ideal privacy-sensitive system should satisfy. Data protection authoritiescan use the FIPPS to regulate practitioners regarding how, when, and for what purpose data canbe collected, used, and disclosed [47]. Nissenbaum’s “decision heuristic” [33] includes a series ofguidelines articulated in nine steps, which can evaluate the “system or practice in question.”However, both the privacy engineering and guidelines-based approaches look at privacy fromthe organization’s perspective (i.e., the risks for their business) rather than the end-users’ view(i.e., end-users’ perception). The likelihood and severity scores are best guesses from these experts,which might be different from the actual user perceptions of the privacy problems. Furthermore,these experts-required privacy frameworks are often inaccessible for smaller teams and individualswho do not have resources to hire specialized privacy experts. We design AgilePrivacy to fill thesegaps.2.2 Understanding privacy from users’ perspectiveBeyond the privacy review from the companies’ perspective, HCI & privacy researchers havedeveloped various methods to understand users’ mental models of privacy, such as surveys [5,104],focus groups [25,54], experiments [27] and contextual inquiry [7]. They found that when choosingamong applications with similar functionality, privacy-conscious participants were willing to pay apremium of $1.50 over an initial price of $0.49 when users were presented the requested permissionsof each application side-by-side.These studies can provide valuable insights for policymakers and help companies betterunderstand the desired privacy design, but is less practical in supporting the decision makingin privacy design. First, these studies are costly and often conducted in a retrospective manner (i.e.,when the target system is already deployed). Second, the results can only inform practitioners ofusers’ perception but provides little direct feedback on system design. Differently, AgilePrivacydevelops a storytelling framework to help practitioners communicate their data practice withoutimplementation. Further, AgilePrivacy takes a procedural perspective, allowing users to dive into theprocedure of the data practice and tell practitioners which part of the process might be problematic.2.3 Privacy surveysPrivacy surveys are a common approach to measure users’ privacy attitudes and concerns [8,34,34,62,98] across times [4,53] and demographics [17,24,100]. One notable example is the over 30privacy indexes created by Dr. Alan Westin [53]. These privacy indexes cover the general level ofprivacy concerns of the public as well as the attitudes about specific privacy-related topics, forexample, confidence in organizations that handle personal information, acceptance of a nationalidentification system, and use of medical records for research.A major limitation of these surveys is that participants’ broad, generic privacy attitudes donot match well with context-specific, privacy-related behaviors, either actual or intended [18,60].Barkhuus [7] questioned the viability of obtaining universal answers in terms of people’s ’general’privacy practices, and argued for the use of more specific vocabularies to analyze contextuallygrounded privacy issues. A number of studies [5,49,102] have used the Contextual Integrity [70]framework to construct context-related questions that can help identify established privacy norms.For example, Apthorpe et al. [5] examined a range of settings, devices, and information types tothe context of interest through questions like: "A sleep monitorrecordsaudio of its owner. Howacceptable is it forthe monitorto send this information to [different recipients]?". Contextualprivacy surveys can provide valuable insights to establish privacy norms/guidelines. Still, they areoften insufficient to provide direct feedback to a specific data practice, since these parameterizeddescriptions cannot capture the richness of complex data actions across multiple stakeholders.The surveys generated by AgilePrivacy fall into another group of privacy surveys, namely privacyincident surveys [23,52,104], which collect users’ responses toward a specific scenario, aimingto capture the details of privacy-sensitive contexts. The most relevant work is ethical-responsesurveys [85], in which Schechter et al. [85] run 3,539 factorial vignette surveys (FVS) to study fivescenarios. To study users’ privacy perception through FVS, experimenters need to carefully designthe variants, collect a large number of responses, and analyze the results to illustrate statisticalsignificance. Naturally, FVS is too expensive, in terms of time, cost, and expertise requirement,when data practitioners need a tool to support their decision making in privacy design. Differently,AgilePrivacy reduces the cost significantly by asking participants toactivelyexamining a specificdata practice for privacy concerns. In doing so, AgilePrivacy is a discounted privacy concerninspection method that data practitioners can leverage in a low-cost and fast manner.3 AN OVERVIEW OF AGILEPRIVACYIn this section, we present the design goal and a brief overview of AgilePrivacy.ACM Trans. AgilePrivacy: Preempting Data Use Backlash using the Crowd1:73.1 AgilePrivacy Design GoalsAgilePrivacy is built upon on the framework of "user privacy expectation [21,45,46,56,71]." Recentstudies [48,51] find that the "notice and consent" paradigm is getting less practical. Since each userinteracts with hundreds of services, it is unrealistic to assume users have read through privacypolicies. Instead, the Privacy Bill of Rights, endorsed by the Obama White House [45], arguesthat companies need to understand users’ privacy expectations and behave under the expectation,shifting the burden of privacy protection from individuals to the companies.However, existing solutions to review privacy design suffer from various limitations, such as thelack of users’ perspectives [72,105], high cost [72,85,105], retrospective nature [105], slow reviewprocess [85], and the ability to only offer generic feedback [5,72]. In response to these limitations,we define four properties an ideal user-centered privacy review solution should embody.•Human-centered privacy measurement.User privacy expectation is a human-centeredconcept by nature. It’s more natural to ask end-users to evaluate their privacy expectationsrather than letting experts guess users’ expectations. The technique should collect users’privacy opinions directly and use these opinions to help practitioners identify privacy designflaws.•Low cost, light-weight, and accessible.Existing techniques (e.g., PRAM, FRS) are tooexpensive and time-consuming for day-to-day use. An ideal method should be fast, accessible,and low cost, so practitioners can collect users’ direct feedback quickly and iterate the datapractice design accordingly.•Practical feedback for practitioners.The technique should provide concrete andquantitative feedback to data practitioners, not only which part of the data practice mightbe wrong, but also how severe the problem is (i.e., the percentage of affected people andthe severity of the impact). In this way, practitioners can test different variations to balanceprivacy-relevant design choices with opposing interests.•Consistent and repeatable.The output of an ideal technique should be consistent andrepeatable under certain assumptions (e.g., the same demographic), so different parties (e.g.,companies and privacy regulators) in the privacy discussion can cross-check the user privacyexpectation.3.2 AgilePrivacy challengesAt the heart of AgilePrivacy is a novel approach that guides crowd workers inactivelyexamining aspecific data practice for privacy concerns, which reduces the cost and required resources for privacyconcern inspection. Along with these exciting benefits also come three significant challenges.•Communicating the privacy design to crowd workers. Understanding the details of adata practice requires significant expertise and technical background. For example, pastwork [32] has found that most non-specialists do not understand the details of the FacebookCambridge Analytica data scandal [35,99] even after being exposed to massive press coverage.•Scaffolding the privacy design review. Asking crowd workers to review privacy designis challenging for two reasons: task duration and expertise. When a privacy expert reviewsthe data practice, she needs to enumerate the potential privacy problems and then to assessthe impact and likelihood. This process can take hours to complete; however, most crowdworkers can hardly engage for such a long time. Besides, crowd workers may only have avague understanding of privacy and may be unable to articulate the problem. For example,feedback such as “I just do not like this data practice.” can only provide limited insights forpractitioners.ACM Trans. Comput.-Hum. Interact., Vol. 9, No. 4, Article 1. Publication date: September 2019.
